00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:12.180
First of all, you two
introduce yourselves, but then

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.580
tell us how your various
troupes became involved

00:21:14.580 --> 00:21:16.860
with the Skirball Center.

00:21:16.860 --> 00:21:19.824
HEIDI LATSKY: I'm Heidi Latsky.

00:21:19.824 --> 00:21:21.740
I've been talking to
Michael Harrington, who's

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:24.380
the producer there,
and we were going

00:21:24.380 --> 00:21:27.440
to do something this season.

00:21:27.440 --> 00:21:32.107
And then he actually wanted to
push the company back a year,

00:21:32.107 --> 00:21:33.690
so we were going to
do it next season.

00:21:33.690 --> 00:21:35.980
And I called him up,
and I said, you know,

00:21:35.980 --> 00:21:39.520
it's the 25th
anniversary of the ADA,

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:42.490
so 2015 would be
such a good year

00:21:42.490 --> 00:21:46.671
to celebrate diversity
and inclusion.

00:21:46.671 --> 00:21:48.170
MALE SPEAKER: ADA
is the Americans--

00:21:48.170 --> 00:21:49.310
HEIDI LATSKY: The Americans
with Disabilities Act,

00:21:49.310 --> 00:21:51.360
which you talked about before.

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:54.082
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:21:54.082 --> 00:21:55.540
HEIDI LATSKY: What's
interesting is

00:21:55.540 --> 00:21:59.250
there's a beautiful dance
company out west called Axis,

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:02.120
and they've been around
a really long time doing

00:22:02.120 --> 00:22:03.600
physically integrated work.

00:22:03.600 --> 00:22:08.130
And so he put the two companies
together for this program.

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:09.975
So I think it's really
remarkable, actually.

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:15.150
ITAMAR KUBOVY: Hi,
I'm Itamar Kubovy.

00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:19.680
I'm the executive
producer of Pilobolus.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:21.400
Our relationship
with Skirball really

00:22:21.400 --> 00:22:25.670
had to do initially with
looking to bring the show

00:22:25.670 --> 00:22:28.550
Shadowland to New
York, and wanting

00:22:28.550 --> 00:22:31.540
to find the perfect place
to do it, which we did.

00:22:31.540 --> 00:22:34.540
And Michael, and the rest
of the team at Skirball,

00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:37.830
and we got together about
six, eight months ago

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:39.750
and talked about
what we might do,

00:22:39.750 --> 00:22:42.870
and decided that this
was the right way

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:44.940
to bring the show into New York.

00:22:44.940 --> 00:22:48.810
It's been performing for the
last chunk of time in Europe

00:22:48.810 --> 00:22:52.400
and in Asia, and has never been
done in North America before.

00:22:52.400 --> 00:22:56.830
So it's super exciting for
us to bring the show home

00:22:56.830 --> 00:22:59.856
after having it seen by
so many people that are

00:22:59.856 --> 00:23:04.747
our same sort of home audience.

00:23:04.747 --> 00:23:06.330
MALE SPEAKER: So was
it developed here

00:23:06.330 --> 00:23:08.055
or was it developed
overseas, Shadowland?

00:23:08.055 --> 00:23:09.930
ITAMAR KUBOVY: Shadowland
was developed here.

00:23:09.930 --> 00:23:11.620
It had a sort of
funny beginning.

00:23:11.620 --> 00:23:14.480
We were asked to make a
commercial-- a television

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:16.780
commercial-- for a Hyundai car.

00:23:16.780 --> 00:23:20.880
And the request
came in that said,

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:24.420
could you guys make a car
commercial with no car in it?

00:23:24.420 --> 00:23:29.340
And we thought, OK, we'll try
to put a light behind a shower

00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:30.680
curtain and see what happens.

00:23:30.680 --> 00:23:32.980
And it turned out that
we were able to create

00:23:32.980 --> 00:23:35.260
a convincing sort
of transformation

00:23:35.260 --> 00:23:37.177
of this car in this commercial.

00:23:37.177 --> 00:23:38.760
And then we got a
call from the Oscars

00:23:38.760 --> 00:23:40.260
shortly after that
saying, could you

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:43.600
do the same for the movies
that were nominated this year?

00:23:43.600 --> 00:23:46.460
And suddenly we realized that
this weird advertising inquiry

00:23:46.460 --> 00:23:50.300
turned into an enormously
intense creative project.

00:23:50.300 --> 00:23:51.980
MALE SPEAKER: How
long ago was this?

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:53.813
ITAMAR KUBOVY: This was
about six years ago,

00:23:53.813 --> 00:23:55.207
the first commercial.

00:23:55.207 --> 00:23:57.290
And that was the time that
we sort of rediscovered

00:23:57.290 --> 00:23:59.730
this kind of modern form
of shadow theater, which

00:23:59.730 --> 00:24:01.820
of course has existed forever.

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:05.420
But this was a way of combining
full bodies and this kind

00:24:05.420 --> 00:24:09.490
of mixture of graphic and very
plastic work, where you're

00:24:09.490 --> 00:24:11.000
seeing the bodies,
but you're also

00:24:11.000 --> 00:24:16.330
seeing the images that these
bodies can merge to create.

00:24:16.330 --> 00:24:18.460
It's like that very
rare moment where

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:21.360
you stumble into something
and you, go wait a minute.

00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:26.790
This is not just a piece,
this is not just an idea,

00:24:26.790 --> 00:24:29.490
it's actually sort
of a form that you

00:24:29.490 --> 00:24:31.730
can work in for a long time.

00:24:31.730 --> 00:24:33.730
And so it doesn't happen
very often that you

00:24:33.730 --> 00:24:34.980
bump into something like that.

00:24:34.980 --> 00:24:37.580
It's been very
exciting to work in.

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:39.366
MALE SPEAKER: So is
this kind of something

00:24:39.366 --> 00:24:40.740
that has just
fallen in your lap,

00:24:40.740 --> 00:24:43.680
as you said, but taken you to
a new level of recognition?

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:47.360
Because performing
on the Oscars, right?

00:24:47.360 --> 00:24:50.580
And you've done a collaboration
with Penn and Teller,

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:53.410
I believe, and
some other people.

00:24:53.410 --> 00:24:57.960
So is this, sort of, breathed
new life into the program,

00:24:57.960 --> 00:25:00.799
or is this something--

00:25:00.799 --> 00:25:01.590
ITAMAR KUBOVY: Yes.

00:25:01.590 --> 00:25:02.350
The answer is yes.

00:25:02.350 --> 00:25:03.570
MALE SPEAKER: My question
is, how does this

00:25:03.570 --> 00:25:05.330
compare to your
traditional dance theater

00:25:05.330 --> 00:25:07.220
that you've always
been doing ongoing?

00:25:07.220 --> 00:25:07.900
ITAMAR KUBOVY: You
know, it's interesting,

00:25:07.900 --> 00:25:09.858
because in some sense
it's completely different

00:25:09.858 --> 00:25:12.540
because it's obviously making
shadows behind a screen

00:25:12.540 --> 00:25:14.870
and doing some of the
stuff that you saw.

00:25:14.870 --> 00:25:17.550
But in other ways, the
company for 44 years

00:25:17.550 --> 00:25:20.940
has been committed to mixing
bodies together and move

00:25:20.940 --> 00:25:23.920
from inanimate to
animate-type objects that are

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:27.210
sort of merged and separated.

00:25:27.210 --> 00:25:28.910
So you see something
that looks suddenly

00:25:28.910 --> 00:25:32.110
like a creature that exists,
that's made out of five people.

00:25:32.110 --> 00:25:33.920
And then they all come
apart, and now you

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:37.750
see each individuated
form as a human being.

00:25:37.750 --> 00:25:39.900
And so in some sense,
the big theme--

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:42.480
the big idea-- has stayed
consistent all along,

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:44.450
but the manifestation,
or the application,

00:25:44.450 --> 00:25:48.190
of the idea to a medium, or
a form, that's brand new.

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:50.580
And certainly has been
accessible to a brand

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:52.480
new audience around
the world in a way

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:56.920
that modern dance isn't
always necessarily accessible

00:25:56.920 --> 00:25:57.920
to as broad an audience.

00:25:57.920 --> 00:26:00.600
So its brought a lot of
new people to see us.

00:26:00.600 --> 00:26:03.710
MALE SPEAKER: So Heidi, you
and your wonderful dancers

00:26:03.710 --> 00:26:08.505
as well, you guys are still
more of the traditional--

00:26:08.505 --> 00:26:11.420
I say "traditional"
modern dance,

00:26:11.420 --> 00:26:13.920
but yet you've
incorporated-- obviously

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:17.080
there is Alexandria at
the end who is deaf.

00:26:17.080 --> 00:26:19.520
We have a dancer who
is deaf, and then

00:26:19.520 --> 00:26:23.240
other people in your
troupe have disabilities.

00:26:23.240 --> 00:26:25.194
Is that bringing the
future into the present,

00:26:25.194 --> 00:26:27.610
or would you call that bringing
the past into the present?

00:26:29.499 --> 00:26:31.040
HEIDI LATSKY: That's
a hard question.

00:26:33.730 --> 00:26:35.590
We were just talking about this.

00:26:35.590 --> 00:26:38.390
I would say we're very
nontraditional, even

00:26:38.390 --> 00:26:42.045
in the traditional mode, like
what you're talking about.

00:26:42.045 --> 00:26:44.530
And actually, we've
been exploring

00:26:44.530 --> 00:26:48.550
less traditional ways of opening
this company to the public.

00:26:48.550 --> 00:26:51.370
Like we're doing these movement
installations, one of which

00:26:51.370 --> 00:26:53.380
we're going to do at Skirball.

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:58.420
We just did one in the
atrium at Lincoln Center.

00:26:58.420 --> 00:27:00.520
Also I made a film last year.

00:27:00.520 --> 00:27:02.760
I was commissioned by
Montclair State University,

00:27:02.760 --> 00:27:05.680
and so we're trying
to expand out.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:11.160
Because in our case anyway,
that's our initiative.

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:16.500
Because we are a nontraditional
cast, and our mission

00:27:16.500 --> 00:27:21.680
is to redefine beauty, and
virtuosity, and also dance.

00:27:21.680 --> 00:27:25.937
We just keep trying to find
those venues to promote

00:27:25.937 --> 00:27:27.020
the work that we're doing.

00:27:27.020 --> 00:27:30.660
Because oftentimes,
especially in the dance world,

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:34.300
you tell people you
have an integrated cast,

00:27:34.300 --> 00:27:36.200
or some people
with disabilities,

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:38.510
nontraditional,
unconventional dancers,

00:27:38.510 --> 00:27:41.146
and they shy away from it.

00:27:41.146 --> 00:27:42.020
MALE SPEAKER: Really?

00:27:42.020 --> 00:27:43.092
HEIDI LATSKY: Yes.

00:27:43.092 --> 00:27:43.800
Wouldn't you say?

00:27:46.610 --> 00:27:49.944
MALE SPEAKER: So what
are the critics--

00:27:49.944 --> 00:27:51.360
HEIDI LATSKY: If
you tell somebody

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:53.160
you're a physically
integrated company,

00:27:53.160 --> 00:27:56.060
most people call it
"mixed ability" company,

00:27:56.060 --> 00:28:00.310
which we can't stand,
because it infers

00:28:00.310 --> 00:28:02.690
that there are
different abilities,

00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:05.880
which we know that's not true.

00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:08.680
But normally, people
would associate a company

00:28:08.680 --> 00:28:12.480
like this with people
who are wheelchair users.

00:28:12.480 --> 00:28:16.550
That's an automatic assumption,
which as you can see,

00:28:16.550 --> 00:28:17.856
that's not the case.

00:28:17.856 --> 00:28:19.730
Not that we don't work
with wheelchair users,

00:28:19.730 --> 00:28:22.727
we do, but it's not
always the case.

00:28:22.727 --> 00:28:24.060
You were going to say something.

00:28:24.060 --> 00:28:24.810
MALE SPEAKER: I don't remember
what I was going to say.

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:25.540
HEIDI LATSKY: Did I cut you off?

00:28:25.540 --> 00:28:26.810
MALE SPEAKER: No, no.

00:28:26.810 --> 00:28:28.550
We're here to hear you talk.

00:28:28.550 --> 00:28:30.800
HEIDI LATSKY: I will say
it's been a great year for us

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:36.980
because we have these
presenters now like Skirball.

00:28:36.980 --> 00:28:39.670
Like Michael Harrington
inviting us to do Skirball.

00:28:39.670 --> 00:28:43.290
Or being at Montclair State, or
at the American Dance Festival,

00:28:43.290 --> 00:28:46.350
which are more
traditional venues.

00:28:46.350 --> 00:28:51.652
And so it feels like
we're breaking through.

00:28:51.652 --> 00:28:53.860
MALE SPEAKER: OK, so I want
to actually get over here

00:28:53.860 --> 00:28:56.126
to the dancers and let
some of you folks talk.

00:28:56.126 --> 00:28:57.500
Will you mind
going down the line

00:28:57.500 --> 00:29:00.170
and introducing
yourselves as well?

00:29:00.170 --> 00:29:01.500
NATE BUCHSBAUM: I'm Nate.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:03.890
HEATHER FAVRETTO:
I'm Heather Favretto.

00:29:03.890 --> 00:29:06.719
JERRON HERMAN: Herman.

00:29:06.719 --> 00:29:08.760
SIGN LANGUAGE INTERPRETER:
I'm Alexandria Wailes.

00:29:08.760 --> 00:29:11.360
JILLIAN HOLLIS:
I'm Jillian Hollis.

00:29:11.360 --> 00:29:13.080
MEREDITH FAGES: Meredith Fages.

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:14.770
SAKI MASUDA: Saki Masuda.

00:29:14.770 --> 00:29:16.170
XIMENA BORGES:
I'm Ximena Borges,

00:29:16.170 --> 00:29:20.490
and I'm the composer for
Heidi Latsky's piece.

00:29:20.490 --> 00:29:21.447
And music director.

00:29:21.447 --> 00:29:23.030
MALE SPEAKER: And
music director, yes.

00:29:23.030 --> 00:29:25.397
So the collaborative process.

00:29:25.397 --> 00:29:26.980
I want to talk about
the collaboration

00:29:26.980 --> 00:29:30.150
between the dancers and
the executive directors

00:29:30.150 --> 00:29:31.270
and the choreographers.

00:29:31.270 --> 00:29:33.350
When you guys are coming
up with new material,

00:29:33.350 --> 00:29:40.680
especially the both of you
have such unique, I guess, set

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:42.870
of skills is not
what I want to say.

00:29:42.870 --> 00:29:45.570
It's like the shadow
theatre is so unique,

00:29:45.570 --> 00:29:50.340
and having individuals living
with disabilities is unique

00:29:50.340 --> 00:29:54.580
in itself, that you've got
a very popular dance troupe.

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:56.470
So when it comes to
the collaboration,

00:29:56.470 --> 00:29:59.960
coming up with new pieces, do
both of you start with an idea

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:02.260
and fit into the dancers,
or work with the dancers

00:30:02.260 --> 00:30:03.405
and fit it to the idea?

00:30:09.194 --> 00:30:10.610
ITAMAR KUBOVY: I
think when people

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:13.370
make things, they-- my
experience has been we

00:30:13.370 --> 00:30:16.360
collaborate with a lot of
people in diverse disciplines

00:30:16.360 --> 00:30:18.230
that aren't dance.

00:30:18.230 --> 00:30:21.850
We worked a lot with MIT in
their robotics department,

00:30:21.850 --> 00:30:25.300
and we worked a lot with
puppeteers and magicians.

00:30:25.300 --> 00:30:29.424
We did a piece with Penn
and Teller recently.

00:30:29.424 --> 00:30:30.840
And what you realize
by seeing how

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:33.400
all people from all sorts
of disciplines create,

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:35.220
you realize that whether
they're engineers,

00:30:35.220 --> 00:30:38.680
or whether they're dancers,
the process of making something

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:42.050
is reasonably similar
across the board.

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.420
And it has to do with a
process that's iterative.

00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:49.350
And that you start with
where you know, and you

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:52.540
keep chipping away at what you
don't know until you realize

00:30:52.540 --> 00:30:54.240
that you've gotten somewhere.

00:30:54.240 --> 00:30:56.830
So in a way, we're
constantly working both

00:30:56.830 --> 00:30:59.030
of those ends of that question.

