00:42:48.020 --> 00:42:51.320
was because it wasn't in
the vanguard for me to dance

00:42:51.320 --> 00:42:54.790
or for me you have
a visible performer,

00:42:54.790 --> 00:42:57.860
so I relegated myself
to the background.

00:42:57.860 --> 00:43:02.630
However, now I do feel a
great sense of pride first,

00:43:02.630 --> 00:43:09.550
and ability first, and
then a sense of obligation.

00:43:09.550 --> 00:43:14.125
My goal now is for my
type to be saturated

00:43:14.125 --> 00:43:18.120
in the airwaves
and the atmosphere

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:22.490
because it's so underdeveloped,
or underrepresented.

00:43:22.490 --> 00:43:23.490
So I do feel that sense.

00:43:23.490 --> 00:43:25.031
And as a person of
color too, I think

00:43:25.031 --> 00:43:30.370
there's this compounded view of
that because I know that there

00:43:30.370 --> 00:43:34.620
aren't a lot of African American
people with disabilities on TV

00:43:34.620 --> 00:43:35.120
as well.

00:43:35.120 --> 00:43:37.130
So there's, like,
this other thing.

00:43:37.130 --> 00:43:39.770
But that is all
to say that I find

00:43:39.770 --> 00:43:43.910
the company to be a
great playground for all

00:43:43.910 --> 00:43:45.450
of my questions.

00:43:45.450 --> 00:43:47.820
I grew up not really
in my community.

00:43:47.820 --> 00:43:50.540
And so it's really
great that I'm

00:43:50.540 --> 00:43:53.160
now in the disability
community and taking

00:43:53.160 --> 00:43:54.230
a really active role.

00:43:54.230 --> 00:43:55.470
Because it is part of me.

00:44:00.060 --> 00:44:01.730
SIGN LANGUAGE
INTERPRETER: And I also, I

00:44:01.730 --> 00:44:04.720
don't think that it's
an obligation, per se.

00:44:04.720 --> 00:44:06.580
Not even a duty, necessarily.

00:44:06.580 --> 00:44:09.550
But I just still feel
it's part of the journey.

00:44:09.550 --> 00:44:12.760
I do feel that it is
important to prove

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:15.020
that not only to yourself,
but also to society,

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:18.400
and increase the visibility
and encourage opening

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:21.102
the door for other people.

00:44:21.102 --> 00:44:22.560
There is definitely
a lot of talent

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:26.480
that's not being recognized
and being encouraged.

00:44:26.480 --> 00:44:29.370
It's not just one
person who's obligated.

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:31.190
It does take everyone
to be involved.

00:44:31.190 --> 00:44:32.730
So I feel like all
of these people

00:44:32.730 --> 00:44:36.720
here, when people witness
and watch our show,

00:44:36.720 --> 00:44:42.100
they're seeing both disability
and non-disabled people working

00:44:42.100 --> 00:44:43.710
together.

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:46.070
And there's a
bigger vision here.

00:44:46.070 --> 00:44:50.610
And that really shows
what's possible.

00:44:50.610 --> 00:44:51.296
Flexibility.

00:44:51.296 --> 00:44:54.030
A lot people sometimes are
not sure what to do with you.

00:44:54.030 --> 00:44:55.030
What to do with me.

00:44:55.030 --> 00:44:57.220
They'll think that's
a disabled person.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:44:59.350
But there's so many different
ways to make it work.

00:44:59.350 --> 00:45:00.790
And it's not that big of a deal.

00:45:00.790 --> 00:45:02.790
So you just have to honor
what needs to happen

00:45:02.790 --> 00:45:03.998
as being part of the process.

00:45:03.998 --> 00:45:05.770
But other than that,
you just go with it.

00:45:05.770 --> 00:45:09.150
And I've noticed that
has been really powerful.

00:45:09.150 --> 00:45:12.400
People really respond to
that process, the visibility.

00:45:12.400 --> 00:45:15.350
And I agree with
Jerron is saying

00:45:15.350 --> 00:45:17.080
in terms of artists
of color as well,

00:45:17.080 --> 00:45:19.690
to increase that visibility.

00:45:19.690 --> 00:45:21.710
And as a woman as well.

00:45:21.710 --> 00:45:24.840
So that's sort of a
triple whammy there.

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:29.144
So yes, we do feel sometimes
like we want to just sort of,

00:45:29.144 --> 00:45:31.310
why bother, you know, and
give up and throw our arms

00:45:31.310 --> 00:45:34.300
up in the air sometimes, because
it can be really frustrating.

00:45:34.300 --> 00:45:35.900
But to recognize
that we are making

00:45:35.900 --> 00:45:38.350
strides in increasing
visibility,

00:45:38.350 --> 00:45:40.150
and it's a moment
by moment change.

00:45:40.150 --> 00:45:43.070
Like Heidi said, for the
company it's been a great year,

00:45:43.070 --> 00:45:45.350
and also for me too, it's
been an excellent year.

00:45:45.350 --> 00:45:49.080
I've just been very,
very busy as an artist.

00:45:49.080 --> 00:45:52.320
I've gone through some long
dry spells of lots of auditions

00:45:52.320 --> 00:45:54.210
and not having very much
going on for myself,

00:45:54.210 --> 00:45:55.870
so you just have to
kind of roll with it.

00:45:55.870 --> 00:45:57.494
That's part of the
business in general,

00:45:57.494 --> 00:45:59.067
and that's applicable to anyone.

00:45:59.067 --> 00:45:59.900
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:45:59.900 --> 00:46:01.304
Thank you so much.

00:46:01.304 --> 00:46:02.970
MALE SPEAKER: So how
would you recommend

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:04.594
that we spread the word?

00:46:04.594 --> 00:46:06.510
I mean, do you have
educational opportunities?

00:46:06.510 --> 00:46:08.110
Do you have volunteer
opportunities?

00:46:08.110 --> 00:46:08.795
How do we get involved?

00:46:08.795 --> 00:46:10.128
How do we let other people know?

00:46:14.083 --> 00:46:15.249
HEIDI LATSKY: More specific?

00:46:18.960 --> 00:46:22.200
MALE SPEAKER: If I wanted to
get involved and help raise

00:46:22.200 --> 00:46:24.610
awareness for either
of your troupes, or do

00:46:24.610 --> 00:46:26.810
you have classes that you
teach when people want

00:46:26.810 --> 00:46:28.560
to get involved in dancing.

00:46:28.560 --> 00:46:29.950
If someone may
have disabilities,

00:46:29.950 --> 00:46:32.116
if they don't know where
to start, where do they go?

00:46:36.402 --> 00:46:38.360
HEIDI LATSKY: I don't
teach on a regular basis,

00:46:38.360 --> 00:46:43.370
although we are starting--
the DOE is very interested now

00:46:43.370 --> 00:46:46.972
in getting us into the schools.

00:46:46.972 --> 00:46:48.180
MALE SPEAKER: Public schools?

00:46:48.180 --> 00:46:49.340
HEIDI LATSKY:
Public schools, yes.

00:46:49.340 --> 00:46:51.340
So Jerron is teaching
there right now, actually,

00:46:51.340 --> 00:46:52.300
in one school.

00:46:52.300 --> 00:46:56.170
And we're working
on a whole workshop

00:46:56.170 --> 00:46:59.340
to maybe be an
annual thing, or just

00:46:59.340 --> 00:47:01.820
to get this work into
the schools, which

00:47:01.820 --> 00:47:04.160
I think is desperately needed.

00:47:04.160 --> 00:47:09.300
We have a website, people
can contact us at any time.

00:47:09.300 --> 00:47:12.810
We don't have a school but
we're always rehearsal,

00:47:12.810 --> 00:47:14.290
and we're actually
always looking

00:47:14.290 --> 00:47:18.390
for performers and for people
to support our movement,

00:47:18.390 --> 00:47:20.280
because I do feel
like it's a movement.

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:22.660
When you're asking the
people with disabilities

00:47:22.660 --> 00:47:29.010
I feel like this company, and
me specifically, since 2006

00:47:29.010 --> 00:47:32.250
I've become more and
more of an advocate.

00:47:32.250 --> 00:47:36.300
And I wouldn't say it's as
an advocate for disability,

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:40.761
but it's really for-- we coined
it-- the beauty of difference,

00:47:40.761 --> 00:47:41.260
right?

00:47:41.260 --> 00:47:43.070
The beauty of the individual.

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:46.460
And that's really become
very important to us all.

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:49.730
So we encourage
people, we welcome

00:47:49.730 --> 00:47:52.440
people to become
part of the process,

00:47:52.440 --> 00:47:55.257
support us in this mission.

00:47:55.257 --> 00:47:56.840
MALE SPEAKER: Does
Pilobolus, you guys

00:47:56.840 --> 00:47:58.530
have-- you guys teach
workshops, right?

00:47:58.530 --> 00:48:00.279
ITAMAR KUBOVY: We teach
quite a bit, yeah.

00:48:00.279 --> 00:48:04.860
And I think we actually have a
program on the road as we tour,

00:48:04.860 --> 00:48:08.090
and in Connecticut,
where our studio is

00:48:08.090 --> 00:48:11.680
during the summers,
where we essentially

00:48:11.680 --> 00:48:16.920
look for non-dancers and put
them together with dancers

00:48:16.920 --> 00:48:19.690
in a creative process workshop.

00:48:19.690 --> 00:48:21.660
And we work with
multi-generational groups,

00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:25.340
and people who have
very little ability

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:28.440
to do acrobatics, but
then have a huge ability

00:48:28.440 --> 00:48:31.130
to do all sorts of other
things that mixed together

00:48:31.130 --> 00:48:35.184
with difference allows for
great things to happen.

00:48:35.184 --> 00:48:36.350
So we do that in the summer.

00:48:36.350 --> 00:48:39.320
And all the information
there is also on our website.

00:48:39.320 --> 00:48:41.860
And the Ford Foundation
has been supporting us

00:48:41.860 --> 00:48:44.530
over the last couple of years
to bring that programming

00:48:44.530 --> 00:48:47.380
to different cities where
we're going to perform.

00:48:47.380 --> 00:48:50.710
And around the country in the
US, we show up in a week early

00:48:50.710 --> 00:48:54.660
and then reach out to a whole
bunch of different groups,

00:48:54.660 --> 00:48:58.110
and sort of introduce them
to give them a, sort of,

00:48:58.110 --> 00:49:02.500
an immersive sense in what
it is that we do and we do a.

00:49:02.500 --> 00:49:04.035
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:49:04.035 --> 00:49:06.185
Question over here.

00:49:06.185 --> 00:49:08.044
AUDIENCE: That was
really fascinating.

00:49:08.044 --> 00:49:10.085
I didn't read the fine
print of the announcement,

00:49:10.085 --> 00:49:12.210
and so I didn't realize
until you got up here

00:49:12.210 --> 00:49:16.790
that it was troupe
with disabilities.

00:49:16.790 --> 00:49:19.910
That was a really
interesting experience.

00:49:19.910 --> 00:49:25.400
And I guess also
my wife is deaf,

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:29.610
I know a tiny, tiny
bit of sign language.

00:49:29.610 --> 00:49:31.250
Not very good about that.

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:32.890
But I did pick up
some of that, and I

00:49:32.890 --> 00:49:37.105
was curious what was being
said there in the performance.

00:49:42.990 --> 00:49:45.440
SIGN LANGUAGE INTERPRETER:
So I'm talking to Garret

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:47.870
and I was wondering if he
understood what I was saying.

00:49:47.870 --> 00:49:49.440
And I was actually
signing the lyrics

00:49:49.440 --> 00:49:50.689
to Somewhere Over the Rainbow.

00:49:53.350 --> 00:49:55.860
Yeah, but actually
understand the process

00:49:55.860 --> 00:49:59.910
was that when Heidi and I
collaborate, and we were

00:49:59.910 --> 00:50:01.920
discussing it,
she asked me to do

00:50:01.920 --> 00:50:04.030
an ASL translation of the song.

00:50:04.030 --> 00:50:07.120
And then I went back to
the beginning of the lyrics

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:13.530
and I was creating, an
accumulation of the vocabulary.

00:50:13.530 --> 00:50:16.940
So this is first, and then
second, and then third.

00:50:16.940 --> 00:50:19.140
And so I was sort of
accumulating the vocabulary,

00:50:19.140 --> 00:50:21.510
and then I was just
turning up to speed.

00:50:21.510 --> 00:50:24.010
So from the beginning
to the very end

00:50:24.010 --> 00:50:25.930
I was signing the
lyrics of the song.

00:50:25.930 --> 00:50:28.964
And I was incorporating
the movement as well.

00:50:28.964 --> 00:50:29.880
MALE SPEAKER: OK good.

00:50:29.880 --> 00:50:32.379
I don't feel bad about
not recognizing it.

00:50:32.379 --> 00:50:34.420
SIGN LANGUAGE INTERPRETER:
No, it's totally fine.

00:50:34.420 --> 00:50:37.124
It's totally fine.

00:50:37.124 --> 00:50:39.040
HEIDI LATSKY: Another
reason that you probably

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:41.810
didn't get it is that
I took her face away.

00:50:44.470 --> 00:50:45.830
And I didn't know that.

00:50:45.830 --> 00:50:48.280
So at the first rehearsal
when I said to Alexandria,

00:50:48.280 --> 00:50:49.710
can you sign it?

00:50:49.710 --> 00:50:51.400
Just be neutral in your face.

00:50:51.400 --> 00:50:54.950
And that's like taking a
whole chunk of the language

00:50:54.950 --> 00:50:56.840
out of the language, right?

00:50:56.840 --> 00:50:59.080
Which I didn't realize
until that experience,

00:50:59.080 --> 00:51:03.920
but I didn't want this
section of dancing

00:51:03.920 --> 00:51:06.130
to just be her signing.

00:51:06.130 --> 00:51:10.080
I really wanted it to be a lot
more internal and evocative.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:19.167
Now I know how challenging
that was for Alexandria.

